  <content>
    <title>Quality Attribute Trade-offs in Architecture</title>

    <summary>Quality attributes often conflict: improving one typically degrades another. This methodology covers the ISO 25010 model, common attribute conflict pairs, architecture style trade-offs (monolith vs microservices), CAP theorem data trade-offs, and communication pattern trade-offs as the factual basis for any trade-off decision. Includes a strict trigger list, a step-by-step how-to, a copy-paste ADR template, lift-and-paste prompts and a verify checklist.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Every architecture choice involves sacrificing one quality to gain another. Without a shared model of which attributes conflict and why, teams make decisions based on gut feel or fashion (cargo-culting). The ISO 25010 quality model provides a systematic vocabulary for quality requirements. CAP theorem and architecture style trade-off tables provide empirically grounded reference points that prevent reinventing these trade-offs from scratch on each project.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <p>Trigger this methodology automatically when ANY of the following appear in the current task:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Building quality attribute scenarios for ATAM or filling a decision matrix — to identify which pairs are in tension.</item>
        <item>Evaluating architecture style options (monolith, modular monolith, microservices, serverless, event-driven).</item>
        <item>Selecting a data storage strategy where consistency must be weighed against availability or partition tolerance.</item>
        <item>Designing service-to-service communication (sync REST/gRPC vs async queues vs event-driven brokers).</item>
        <item>Writing the "Consequences" section of an ADR — to enumerate explicit gain/loss pairs.</item>
        <item>Reviewing a proposed change whose description contains any of: "scale", "low latency", "always available", "encrypt", "decouple", "extract service", "introduce queue", "switch DB", "rewrite", "cold start".</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>As a substitute for context-specific analysis — these tables are starting points, not verdicts. Your system's actual trade-offs may differ.</item>
        <item>When a single quality attribute clearly dominates all others for your use case — simplify instead of balancing a full ISO 25010 analysis.</item>
        <item>For pure code-style or formatting decisions with no runtime quality impact.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <p>Apply the following ordered steps. Do not skip steps; each produces an artifact consumed by the next.</p>
      <step>Identify the decision under analysis. Write a single-sentence statement: "We must decide whether to X instead of Y." Capture context: team size, traffic, compliance, time horizon.</step>
      <step>Enumerate the affected ISO 25010 characteristics from the eight listed in the iso-25010 section. Mark each as Primary (must improve), Secondary (acceptable to maintain), or Sacrificial (acceptable to degrade).</step>
      <step>Cross-reference the common-conflicts list. For every Primary attribute, list which Secondary or Sacrificial attributes it typically degrades and by approximately how much (qualitative: small/medium/large, or quantitative if data exists).</step>
      <step>If the decision involves architecture style, fill the architecture-style scoring table from the template using the architecture-style-tradeoffs section as inputs.</step>
      <step>If the decision involves a database or distributed data store, classify each candidate as CP, AP, or hybrid using the cap-theorem section. Reject AP for financial ledgers and CP for high-write social feeds without explicit justification.</step>
      <step>If the decision involves service communication, classify each option as Sync, Async, or Event-driven and copy the impact row from the communication-pattern-tradeoffs example into the ADR.</step>
      <step>Run the llm-prompt below against the populated context to surface trade-offs the human reviewer may have missed. Treat its output as a critique, not a verdict.</step>
      <step>Fill the consequences-template with explicit gain/loss pairs. Every Primary attribute must have at least one Sacrificial counterpart named.</step>
      <step>Run the verify checklist. If any item fails, return to the relevant step.</step>
      <step>Commit the ADR. Re-link from spec.md, design.md, or implementation-plan.md depending on SDD lifecycle stage.</step>
    </how-to>

    <section name="iso-25010">
      <p>ISO 25010 Product Quality Model defines eight top-level quality characteristics, each with sub-characteristics:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Functional Suitability — completeness, correctness, appropriateness.</item>
        <item>Performance Efficiency — time behavior, resource utilization, capacity.</item>
        <item>Compatibility — co-existence, interoperability.</item>
        <item>Usability — learnability, operability, user error protection, accessibility.</item>
        <item>Reliability — availability, fault tolerance, recoverability, maturity.</item>
        <item>Security — confidentiality, integrity, non-repudiation, authenticity, accountability.</item>
        <item>Maintainability — modularity, reusability, analyzability, modifiability, testability.</item>
        <item>Portability — adaptability, installability, replaceability.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="common-conflicts">
      <p>Improving one quality attribute typically degrades another. Common conflict pairs:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Performance vs Maintainability — optimized code is harder to change; abstractions add call overhead.</item>
        <item>Performance vs Portability — hardware-specific optimizations reduce portability.</item>
        <item>Security vs Usability — authentication steps and access controls create friction.</item>
        <item>Security vs Performance — encryption, validation, and audit logging add latency.</item>
        <item>Availability vs Consistency — in distributed systems, maintaining both under partition is impossible (CAP).</item>
        <item>Availability vs Cost — redundancy and failover infrastructure multiplies costs.</item>
        <item>Flexibility vs Performance — dynamic dispatch, plugin architectures, and late binding add overhead.</item>
        <item>Flexibility vs Simplicity — configurability increases cognitive load and bug surface.</item>
        <item>Scalability vs Consistency — horizontal scaling requires relaxing strong consistency guarantees.</item>
        <item>Scalability vs Cost — infrastructure to handle 10x load costs substantially more.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every architectural decision that improves a quality attribute MUST explicitly name which other attribute(s) it degrades and whether that trade-off is acceptable for the current system context. The "Consequences" section of every ADR MUST include a gain/loss pair for each affected attribute.</statement>
        <rationale>Hidden trade-offs (not documenting sacrifices) is the most common cause of production failures that "nobody predicted". Making them explicit converts implicit organizational knowledge into reviewable artifacts.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="architecture-style-tradeoffs">
      <p>Architecture style trade-offs — what each style gains and loses:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Monolith — gets: simplicity, debugging ease, fast local development, single deployment, easy transactions. Loses: independent scaling of components, team autonomy at large scale.</item>
        <item>Modular Monolith — gets: boundary clarity, simpler operations than microservices, testable modules in isolation. Loses: deployment independence (still one artifact), full team autonomy.</item>
        <item>Microservices — gets: independent scaling, team autonomy, technology heterogeneity, isolated failures. Loses: operational complexity, distributed system latency, debugging difficulty, data consistency.</item>
        <item>Serverless — gets: no ops burden, automatic scaling, pay-per-use cost model. Loses: cold start latency, vendor lock-in, difficult local development, limited execution duration.</item>
        <item>Event-driven — gets: loose coupling, extensibility, resilience to downstream failures. Loses: eventual consistency, complex debugging, harder to trace causality.</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good" title="Architecture style decision for fintech startup">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Context: Series A fintech, 8 engineers, MVP in 6 months, PCI-DSS required, 10K tx/day.

ATAM-style scenario analysis:
Scenario 1: PCI-DSS Audit (H, H)
  Monolith: single scope, larger blast radius → Medium risk
  Microservices: isolated PCI scope to payment service → Low risk

Scenario 2: Developer Onboarding (M, L)
  Monolith: single codebase, easy to understand → Low risk
  Microservices: multiple repos, complex local setup → High risk

Scenario 3: 50x Traffic Spike (H, H)
  Monolith: vertical scaling only → High risk
  Microservices: independent scaling of hot services → Low risk

Decision: Modular Monolith + extracted Payment Service (hybrid)
Trade-offs accepted:
  Get: fast development velocity, minimal PCI scope, clear module boundaries, easier onboarding
  Lose: some future extraction effort, two deployment pipelines, not full service independence]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="cap-theorem">
      <p>CAP Theorem: a distributed system can guarantee at most two of Consistency, Availability, and Partition tolerance simultaneously. Since network partitions always occur in distributed systems, the practical choice is between CP and AP.</p>
      <list>
        <item>CP (Consistency + Partition tolerance) — gets: correctness, no stale reads. Loses: availability during network partitions. Examples: PostgreSQL clusters, CockroachDB, etcd.</item>
        <item>AP (Availability + Partition tolerance) — gets: always available even during partitions. Loses: immediate consistency (eventual consistency model). Examples: Cassandra, DynamoDB (default), Couchbase.</item>
        <item>CA (Consistency + Availability) — possible only on a single node with no partitions. Not a realistic distributed option.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every data storage decision MUST state which CAP trade-off is acceptable for the domain. Payment systems and financial ledgers MUST use CP databases. User preference, activity feeds, and session data CAN use AP databases. Mixed requirements MUST use a hybrid: CP for transactional data, AP for read-optimized projections.</statement>
        <rationale>Choosing AP for a payment ledger causes data loss on partition recovery. Choosing CP for a social feed adds unnecessary latency. Mismatched CAP choice is the most common source of data consistency incidents.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="communication-pattern-tradeoffs">
      <p>Service communication pattern trade-offs:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Synchronous (REST, gRPC) — gets: simplicity, immediate response, easy debugging, strong consistency. Loses: coupling (caller blocked on callee), cascade failures, scaling bottlenecks at slow callees.</item>
        <item>Asynchronous (message queues) — gets: decoupling, resilience (caller continues when callee is slow/down), independent scaling. Loses: complexity, eventual consistency, harder to debug, need idempotency.</item>
        <item>Event-driven — gets: very loose coupling, extensibility (add consumers without modifying producers), high throughput. Loses: eventual consistency, complex causality tracing, operational overhead of broker.</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good" title="Hybrid sync/async order processing">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Context: E-commerce platform, 10K orders/day, payment gateway timeouts causing failures.

Quality attribute impact of options:
| Attribute      | Sync  | Full Async | Hybrid | Saga      |
|----------------|-------|------------|--------|-----------|
| Consistency    | Strong| Eventual   | Mixed  | Eventual+compensation |
| User latency   | High  | Low        | Medium | Low       |
| Complexity     | Low   | High       | Medium | Very High |
| Reliability    | Coupled| Decoupled | Mixed  | Decoupled |

Chosen: Hybrid
- Sync: validate + reserve inventory (2s timeout)
- Async (Kafka): payment, shipping prep, notification

Trade-offs accepted:
  Get: fast checkout response (<500ms), resilience to downstream failures, independent scaling
  Lose: immediate payment confirmation, strong consistency, simple debugging

Implementation requirements from trade-off:
  - All async handlers MUST be idempotent
  - Dead letter queue for failed processing retry
  - WebSocket for real-time order status]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="checklist-tradeoff-analysis">
      <p>Run this checklist for every non-trivial architectural decision. Each item must be ticked or explicitly waived in the ADR.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>Decision statement is a single sentence that names exactly one alternative being chosen and one being rejected.</check>
        <check>Affected ISO 25010 characteristics are tagged Primary / Secondary / Sacrificial.</check>
        <check>For every Primary attribute, at least one Sacrificial attribute is named (no "everything wins" claims).</check>
        <check>If distributed data is involved, CAP class (CP / AP / Hybrid) is stated for every storage component.</check>
        <check>If services communicate, every link is classified as Sync / Async / Event-driven with reason.</check>
        <check>Quantitative thresholds are present where measurable (p95 latency, RPO, RTO, error budget, $/month).</check>
        <check>Mitigations are listed for each Sacrificial attribute (e.g. "eventual consistency mitigated by idempotent handlers + DLQ").</check>
        <check>An exit criterion is defined: under what observable condition would we revisit and possibly reverse the decision.</check>
        <check>The decision is recorded as an ADR file under the project's adr/ directory and linked from spec.md or design.md.</check>
        <check>The "Consequences" section enumerates explicit gain/loss pairs as required by the rule in common-conflicts.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="commands">
      <p>Concrete commands the agent can execute to support trade-off analysis. Substitute project paths as needed.</p>
      <commands>
        <command name="list-existing-adrs">find . -type f \( -path "*/adr/*.md" -o -path "*/adrs/*.md" -o -path "*/decisions/*.md" \) | sort</command>
        <command name="grep-quality-attributes">grep -RInE "scalab|availab|consisten|latenc|throughput|maintainab|portabil|secur" --include="*.md" docs/ adr/ 2>/dev/null</command>
        <command name="new-adr-from-template">cp templates/adr-tradeoff-template.md adr/ADR-$(date +%Y%m%d)-SLUG.md</command>
        <command name="lint-adr-has-consequences">grep -L "## Consequences" adr/*.md || echo "all ADRs contain Consequences"</command>
        <command name="lint-adr-mentions-cap">grep -RIL "CP\|AP\|CAP" adr/*.md | xargs -I{} echo "MISSING CAP classification: {}"</command>
        <command name="check-tradeoff-pairs">grep -E "Get:|Lose:|Gain:|Sacrifice:" adr/*.md | sort | uniq -c</command>
      </commands>
    </section>

    <section name="adr-template">
      <p>Copy this verbatim into a new ADR file and fill the placeholders. The headings are mandatory.</p>
      <template path="templates/adr-tradeoff-template.md" purpose="ADR with explicit quality attribute trade-offs"/>
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# ADR-NNNN: <decision title>

Status: Proposed | Accepted | Superseded by ADR-MMMM
Date: YYYY-MM-DD
Deciders: <names or roles>

## Context
<1-3 paragraphs: business goal, system state, forcing functions, constraints (team size, traffic, compliance, deadline)>

## Decision
We will <chosen option> instead of <rejected option(s)>.

## Quality Attribute Impact (ISO 25010)
| Attribute              | Role        | Direction | Magnitude | Notes / Quantitative target          |
|------------------------|-------------|-----------|-----------|--------------------------------------|
| Performance Efficiency | Primary     | improves  | medium    | p95 < 200 ms at 1k RPS               |
| Reliability            | Primary     | improves  | large     | 99.95% monthly availability          |
| Maintainability        | Sacrificial | degrades  | medium    | +1 service to operate                |
| Security               | Secondary   | unchanged | -         | No new exposed surface               |
| Portability            | Sacrificial | degrades  | small     | Couples to broker X                  |

## CAP Classification (if applicable)
- Storage A: CP (PostgreSQL primary)  — required for ledger correctness
- Storage B: AP (Redis cache)         — staleness ≤ 30s acceptable

## Communication Patterns
- Edge → API: Sync REST  (low complexity, browser compatible)
- API → Worker: Async Kafka (decoupling, resilience to spikes)

## Considered Alternatives
1. <alt 1> — rejected because <quality attribute impact>.
2. <alt 2> — rejected because <quality attribute impact>.

## Consequences
Gain:
- <gain 1 tied to a Primary attribute>
- <gain 2>

Lose:
- <loss 1 tied to a Sacrificial attribute>
- <loss 2>

Mitigations:
- <mitigation for each loss>

## Exit Criterion
Revisit this decision when <observable condition>, e.g. "p95 latency > 500ms for 7 consecutive days" or "team size > 25".

## Links
- spec.md#requirement-id
- design.md#component-id
- runbook.md#component-id]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-prompt">
      <prompt purpose="quality attribute trade-off analysis">
<![CDATA[Analyze quality attribute trade-offs for [architectural decision].

Current system: [Brief description of current state]
Proposed change: [Description of proposed change]

For each quality attribute pair that may conflict:
1. Identify the trade-off (what improves, what degrades)
2. Quantify impact if possible (percentages, response times, etc.)
3. Assess if trade-off is acceptable for [context]
4. Suggest mitigations for negative impacts

Focus especially on:
- Performance vs Maintainability
- Security vs Usability
- Consistency vs Availability
- Flexibility vs Simplicity

Conclude with: Is this trade-off profile acceptable for a [type of system]?]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="adr critique against trade-off rules">
<![CDATA[You are a software architect reviewing the ADR pasted below.
Apply the trade-off-quality-attributes methodology strictly.

Check and report PASS/FAIL for each item:
1. Decision statement names one chosen and one rejected option.
2. ISO 25010 attributes are tagged Primary / Secondary / Sacrificial.
3. Every Primary attribute has at least one named Sacrificial counterpart.
4. CAP classification (CP / AP / Hybrid) is stated for any distributed storage.
5. Each service-to-service link is labeled Sync / Async / Event-driven.
6. Quantitative thresholds (p95, RPO, RTO, error budget, $/mo) appear where measurable.
7. Mitigations are listed for every Sacrificial attribute.
8. An exit criterion (reversal condition) is present.
9. Consequences section enumerates explicit Gain/Lose pairs.

For every FAIL, propose the smallest concrete edit that fixes it.

ADR:
<<<
[paste ADR markdown here]
>>>]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="verify">
      <p>Apply this verify procedure before marking the trade-off analysis as done.</p>
      <verify>
        <step>Open the ADR. Confirm headings: Context, Decision, Quality Attribute Impact, Considered Alternatives, Consequences, Exit Criterion. Missing heading → fix.</step>
        <step>Run grep -E "Gain:|Lose:" &lt;adr-file&gt; — both substrings must appear at least once. If not, the rule in common-conflicts is violated; rewrite Consequences.</step>
        <step>For every Primary row in the Quality Attribute Impact table, find at least one Sacrificial row in the same table. If none, ask: "What am I really sacrificing?" and add the missing row.</step>
        <step>For each storage component, confirm a CAP label exists. If missing, add CP/AP/Hybrid + one-line justification.</step>
        <step>For each service link, confirm Sync/Async/Event-driven label and one-line reason.</step>
        <step>Run the adr-critique LLM prompt above; resolve every FAIL.</step>
        <step>Confirm the exit criterion is observable (a metric, threshold, or event), not subjective ("when it feels slow" → not acceptable).</step>
        <step>Link the ADR from spec.md, design.md, or implementation-plan.md depending on SDD lifecycle stage; commit the ADR and the link in the same change.</step>
      </verify>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Everything wins" ADRs that claim a decision improves all quality attributes with no sacrifice.</description>
        <reason>Hidden sacrifices surface as production incidents the team did not anticipate. Force the author to name a Sacrificial attribute.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing AP storage for a financial ledger to "stay available".</description>
        <reason>Eventual consistency on money-movement causes data loss on partition recovery. Use CP and a queue for back-pressure instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Adopting microservices for a 5-engineer team to "scale later".</description>
        <reason>Operational overhead degrades Maintainability and team velocity before any scale benefit materializes. Start with a Modular Monolith.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using full async/event-driven communication everywhere by default.</description>
        <reason>Eventual consistency and complex tracing impose a Maintainability tax that is unjustified for low-traffic synchronous flows.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <warning>Trade-off tables are reference points, not verdicts. A wrong default applied without context is worse than no default at all.</warning>
    </section>

